@doc """
Locks in the typecheck improvements made when generic impl method bodies
were turned on (see check.rs `check_impl_block`). Each call below exercises
a stdlib generic-impl method whose body relies on a typecheck fix that
landed alongside the body-checking flip:

- `Option<T>::unwrap` -> `infer_match` must treat `Type::Parameter(T)` as
  meaningful when aggregating arm result types and must skip diverging
  arms (`panic`). Pre-fix the result aggregated to `Unit` and conflicted
  with the declared `-> T` return type.

- `Option<T>::map<U>` -> generic methods on inherent generic impls must
  body-check (Stage 3 + Stage 1). Inside the body, `Option.Some(f(val))`
  needs the struct/enum-literal generic-args-from-field-value inference
  to bind `U` from `f`'s return type.

- `List<T>::filter` and `List<T>::map<U>` -> same generic body-check path,
  exercised against the more complex `List` impl.

Regressing any of these would also break the stdlib build, but having an
explicit lang-level test makes the intent visible and gives a focused
failure surface.
"""
fn main
  some: Option<Int> = Option.Some(7)
  some.unwrap().print()

  doubled =
    some.map(fn (x: Int) -> Int x * 2 end)
  doubled.unwrap().print()

  none: Option<Int> = Option.None
  (none.or(99)).print()

  evens =
    [1, 2, 3, 4, 5].filter(fn (n: Int) -> Bool n % 2 == 0 end)
  evens.length().print()

  labels =
    [1, 2, 3].map(fn (n: Int) -> String "item_#{n}" end)

  match labels.get(0)
    Option.Some(s) -> s.print()
    Option.None -> "missing".print()
  end
end
